# Git Glide GUI line-ending policy
#
# Why this file exists:
# Different operating systems historically use different text line endings:
#
# - Windows normally uses CRLF:
#     Carriage Return + Line Feed
#     Written as: \r\n
#
# - Linux and macOS normally use LF:
#     Line Feed only
#     Written as: \n
#
# - Older classic Mac OS used CR:
#     Carriage Return only
#     Written as: \r
#     This is mostly obsolete today.
#
# Git stores text files most cleanly when line endings are normalized.
# Without a clear policy, the same file can appear changed only because
# one editor converted LF to CRLF or CRLF to LF. That creates noisy diffs,
# unnecessary merge conflicts, and confusing release changes.
#
# Project policy:
# - Windows launcher files and PowerShell source use CRLF because this is a
#   Windows-first WinForms/PowerShell application.
# - Documentation, JSON metrics, manifests, Python, YAML, shell scripts,
#   and Git metadata use LF because they are often read by Git, CI tools,
#   Python, Linux/macOS tools, and release scripts.
# - Binary/archive files are never normalized as text.
#
# Important:
# - The rules below are the source of truth for this repository.
# - After changing this file, run:
#     git add .gitattributes
#     git add --renormalize .
#     git diff --cached --check
#     git commit -m "Normalize repository line endings"

* text=auto

# Windows launcher scripts
# These are normally edited and executed directly on Windows.
*.bat  text eol=crlf
*.cmd  text eol=crlf

# PowerShell source
# Git Glide GUI is a Windows-first WinForms/PowerShell application.
# Keep all PowerShell-related files consistent as CRLF to avoid mixed policy noise.
*.ps1  text eol=crlf
*.psm1 text eol=crlf
*.psd1 text eol=crlf

# Cross-platform scripts and configuration text files
# Keep these as LF because they are commonly used by Git, Python, CI tools,
# Linux/macOS shells, and YAML parsers.
*.py   text eol=lf
*.sh   text eol=lf
*.yml  text eol=lf
*.yaml text eol=lf

# Documentation and structured data
# Keep these as LF so release docs, metrics snapshots, manifests,
# and generated reports do not create CRLF/LF churn.
*.md   text eol=lf
*.txt  text eol=lf
*.json text eol=lf
*.csv  text eol=lf


# Git metadata/helpers
# These should stay LF and predictable across all environments.
.gitattributes text eol=lf
.gitignore     text eol=lf

# Binary/archive files
# Never normalize or diff these as text.
*.zip  binary
*.7z   binary
*.tar  binary
*.gz   binary
*.png  binary
*.jpg  binary
*.jpeg binary
*.gif  binary
*.ico  binary
*.exe  binary
*.dll  binary













